ss and use ReflectionMemberAccessor to create instances. However, I have to be cautious because mock makers typically don’t mock classes, just interface dependencies. If the component's field is a private static final class, I have to ensure the annotations and plugin settings don’t cause conflicts during testing. It's quite a complex setup to navigate!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining module mocking issues**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the challenges of subclass mocking from a non-exported named module. If there's any private accessibility in Java modules, using Reflection could fail. The existing module handler test seems to cover the inner ModuleSystem Found rather than MemberAccessor. I’m concerned that changes in the plugin might affect all tests due to the singleton nature of the plugin registry. It could be risky to try creating a resource with a custom ClassLoader context. I’m looking for a way to limit changes just to the specific test!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Isolating test conflicts**\\n\\nI realize I need to isolate tests that seem impossible after running others. Since test order can often be unpredictable, having a global resource can lead to continuous activation and potential conflicts. There's the existing \\\"InstrumentationMemberAccessorTest,\\\" which targets the active class but invokes the default plugin for instrumentation. I think it’s a good idea to keep coverage for each dynamic access class in its own dedicated Java test file. That might lead to cleaner and more manageable testing!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented coverage-focused test additions for `org.mockito.internal.util.reflection.ReflectionMemberAccessor`.\n\nChanged files:\n- Added `tests/src/org.mockito/mockito-core/5.0.0/src/test/java/org_mockito/mockito_core/ReflectionMemberAccessorTest.java`\n  - Exercises Mockito’s public annotation initialization path with `@Mock` and `@InjectMocks`, reaching reflective constructor creation and 